{"id":14881397,"mediaExerciseId":"9f52d57a-8a60-4095-a6ca-80a8ab404c1d","exerciseName":"10","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612375,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":451,"solutions":[{"id":5992647,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to discuss the given statement. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/2a24ae273a117628ab4bc83bb7595b5c/c58755345a3742130ea599f452792330/lateximg_large.png","width":803},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/2a24ae273a117628ab4bc83bb7595b5c/c58755345a3742130ea599f452792330/lateximg.png","width":401}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Alpha** is a statistical metric that indicates when an investor has outperformed the market over a certain period. This is the vertical gap between an asset's predicted return and its actual return.\n\nA **security's beta** indicates the volatility compared to the overall market. This is the predicted degree of change over securities for a 1% change in market portfolio expected excess.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Investors may use alpha and beta to evaluate an investment's return volatility based on prior performance**. Since alpha and beta are derived using past statistical information, no expected earnings or volatility would be similar.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/2a24ae273a117628ab4bc83bb7595b5c/74cf2d3e43d2e431d61d12834ccba2df/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07